@motus In EvaluatorManager.java we have:
```
  public void shutdown() {
    LOG.log(Level.FINEST, "Shutdown EvaluatorManager: {0}", this.evaluatorId);
    this.messageDispatcher.close();
  }
```
Therefore only thing I did to "make sure" that the EvaluatorMessageDispatcher shuts down is to ensuring the thread pool in the dispatcher is closed. In short, EvaluatorMessageDispatcher.close() eventually calls ExecutorService.shutdown( ) (https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ExecutorService.html#shutdown()). However, from the .shutdown documentation:

> There are no guarantees beyond best-effort attempts to stop processing actively executing tasks.  For example, typical implementations will cancel via {@link Thread#interrupt}, so any task that fails to respond to interrupts may never terminate. 

As a result, I think the logging is the best thing we can do from what I know.
